Harford schools expand Face of Addiction Display to travel around the county Faces of Addiction display 
Students at Harford Tech started a Chain of Hope and have included it in the Faces of Addiction display that will travel to Harford County high schools. 
Students at Harford Tech started a Chain of Hope and have included it in the Faces of Addiction display that will travel to Harford County high schools. Staff report The Aegis Privacy Policy 
The Face of Addiction display that was started by Harford Technical High School's Students Against Destructive Decisions organization last year is traveling to nearly every public high school in Harford County this year, as the county school system continues to expand its Heroin Grassroots Initiative with the support of Harford County Government's Office of Drug Control Policy. 
The display includes The Conversation Tree; a Chain of Hope; and a Project Healthy Delivery collection (at Harford Technical High), or a collection for another organization of the host school's choosing. 
"Harford County Public Schools has embedded drug education awareness and character education in our curriculum for over 30 years," Superintendent of Schools Barbara P. Canavan said in a statement. "The community remembers the DARE program and the strong partnership that was forged when law enforcement worked side by side with our teachers speaking with students about the dangers of drug use." 
"Face of Addiction is an outstanding initiative that illustrates what can happen when we allow our curriculum to grow with our students," Canavan continued. "While the Sheriff's Office, Health Department, PTAs and Office of Drug Control Policy support and join us in our drug education efforts, this project is led by the students; it is their passion about educating their peers that has made this possible." 
"Seeing the students' desire to reach out to one another, serves as a reminder that we should continue to engage and empower our youth," she said. "They want to and they will make a difference." 
Eight high schools will host the display for at least two weeks each: 
• Harford Tech – Weeks of Feb. 6 and Feb. 13; 
• Havre de Grace – Weeks of Feb. 20 and Feb. 27; 
• Fallston – Weeks of March 6 and March 13; 
• North Harford – Weeks of March 20 and 27; 
• Bel Air High – Weeks of April 4, April 10 and April 17; 
• Patterson Mill – Weeks of April 24 and May 1; 
• Edgewood – Weeks of May 8 and May 15; 
• C. Milton Wright – Weeks of May 22 and May 29. Faces of Addiction MATT BUTTON | AEGIS STAFF / Baltimore Sun Harford Tech's Mariah Spencer puts up a banner as she and fellow students with Students Against Destructive Decisions (SADD) set up the Face of Addiction display at Harford Tech. Harford Tech's Mariah Spencer puts up a banner as she and fellow students with Students Against Destructive Decisions (SADD) set up the Face of Addiction display at Harford Tech. (MATT BUTTON | AEGIS STAFF / Baltimore Sun) 
The Conversation Tree, a project started by the Albert P. Close Foundation, displays 55 hearts featuring conversation-starting phrases and photos of 29 Harford County residents lost to fatal heroin overdoses. 
Each school will create their own Chain of Hope using their school colors, and the chains will be linked and on display in a final destination to symbolize the strength in uniting together against addiction, according to a Harford Public Schools news release. 
Project Healthy Delivery is a campaign to collect new baby items in original packaging such as pacifiers, bibs, clothes, onesies, diapers, rattles, etc. Nearly 100 babies are born to drug addiction in Harford County each year.
